Title: New Supply Chain Jobs Are Emerging as AI Takes Hold
Description: As AI becomes more prevalent, many businesses are uncertain about how these new technologies will impact the future of supply chain management. While AI can be an effective tool to complement planning, order management, and inventory tracking, it’s unlikely to make human employees entirely obsolete. Instead, jobs will shift from rote tasks to more analytical ones, in which humans and machines collaborate to create new value. To succeed in this new environment, supply chain leaders should invest in hiring and training for these new skillsets, identify areas for automation, and think strategically about where and when to incorporate new tools. The future of supply chain will be all about collaboration between humans and machines, enabling businesses to deliver greater levels of sustainability and efficiency from end to end.

Title: 3 Questions About AI That Nontechnical Employees Should Be Able to Answer
Description: There are three important questions that any member of your team should be able to answer about AI: How does artificial intelligence work? What is it good at? And what should it never do? Team members who aren’t responsible for building an AI system should nonetheless know how it processes information and answers questions. Learning what machine learning is good at quickly helps someone to see what machine learning is not good at. Problems that are novel, or which lack meaningful data to explain them, remain squarely in the realm of human specialties. Help your employees to understand this difference by showing them tools they already use that are powered by AI, either within the organization or outside it (such as social media advertising or streaming service recommendations). These examples will help team members to understand AI’s enormous potential, but also its limitations. Just because machine learning can solve a problem does not mean it should do so.
